                                                        <ul class="info-bar info-no-author-img">
                            				             <li class="author-desc multiple-author">
                                    <h2><span>by </span><span class="author-name-no-email">Shannon  Firth </span><br>                                        	Contributing Writer                                    </h2>
                                </li>
                                                            
                            </ul>
                                                      <div class="body-content">
                            <div class="tablet-ad-wrap-container">
								<div id="tablet-ad-52882" class="ad-slot ad-right  tablet-ad"></div>                            
                                 
                              </div>
                                <p>WASHINGTON  --  The word in the District this week is that annual health spending will rise 6% over roughly a decade, according to the Centers for Medicare &amp; Medicaid Services (CMS). Also, CMS observed the 50-year anniversary of its two landmark programs, Medicaid and Medicare, with a bit of pageantry.</p>
<p><strong>Health Spending to Rise Nearly 6% Annually Through 2024</strong></p>
<div class="ad-slot ad-right mobile-ad" ></div><div class="ad-slot ad-left desktop-ad"></div><p>Health <a href="http://www.medpagetoday.com/PublicHealthPolicy/Washington-Watch/52819" target="_blank">spending in the U.S. is expected to grow by an average of 5.8%</a> annually through 2024, while spending on physician services is expected to grow by smaller amounts, CMS officials said Tuesday.</p>
<p>The spending growth is largely due to the major expansions in health insurance coverage under the Affordable Care Act (ACA), as well as stronger expected economic growth and the aging of the population, <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/pub/sean-keehan/1a/194/b06" target="_blank">Sean Keehan, MA</a>, an economist in CMS's Office of the Actuary, said at a briefing here sponsored by <a href="http://content.healthaffairs.org/content/early/2015/07/15/hlthaff.2015.0600" target="_blank"><em>Health Affairs</em></a>.</p>
<p>"Although this growth is expected to be faster than in recent past, it's still slower than we've seen in the past 3 decades prior to the recession, [when] growth was roughly 9%," he said.</p>
<p><strong>CMS Salutes 50 Years of Medicaid and Medicare ...</strong></p>
<p>CMS marked <a href="http://www.medpagetoday.com/PublicHealthPolicy/Medicare/52843" target="_blank">the 50th anniversary of its namesake programs</a> by recalling their start and recounting their achievements at a press event here on Wednesday.</p>
<div class="ad-slot ad-left tablet-ad"></div><div class="ad-slot ad-right mobile-ad"></div><div class="ad-slot ad-right desktop-ad"></div><p>"Here's what we're celebrating: more than a generation of seniors who have lived their retirements with medical care they needed without depleting their life savings," said <a href="https://www.cms.gov/About-CMS/leadership/" target="_blank">Andy Slavitt</a>, acting administrator for CMS. Slavitt also noted the millions of disabled Americans and children the programs have helped.</p>
<p>Department of Health and Human Services <a href="http://www.hhs.gov/about/leadership/secretary/sylvia-mathews-burwell/index.html" target="_blank">Secretary Sylvia Burwell</a> joked that she had a lot in common with Medicare and Medicaid, having just turned 50 herself and having just joined social media.</p>
<p><strong>... And Politicians Cast Predictions on Medicare's Next 50 Years</strong></p>
<p>Predicting <a href="http://www.medpagetoday.com/PublicHealthPolicy/Medicare/52832" target="_blank">the path ahead for Medicare</a> can be challenging  --  or perhaps it can be as simple as which side of aisle frames one's view.</p>
<p><a href="http://www.wyden.senate.gov" target="_blank">Sen. Ron Wyden (D-Ore.)</a>, ranking member of the Senate Finance Committee, predicts four areas in which Medicare could be a leader in clinical care, while <a href="https://kevinbrady.house.gov" target="_blank">Rep. Kevin Brady (R-Texas</a>), chairman of the House Ways and Means Health Subcommittee, wants the future to focus on efficiencies. Both men, speaking here at a briefing hosted by the <em>National Journal,</em> stressed that bipartisan support will be necessary for any changes to<a href="http://www.medpagetoday.com/MedPageTodayat10/Medicareat50/50718?preview=1" target="_blank"> the 50-year-old program</a>.</p>
<div class="tablet-ad-wrap-container"><div class="ad-slot ad-right tablet-ad"></div><div class="ad-slot ad-right tablet-ad"></div></div><div class="ad-slot ad-right desktop-ad"></div><div class="ad-slot ad-right mobile-ad"></div><p>Medicare and Medicaid combined provide healthcare to more than 111 million Americans, according to <a href="http://jama.jamanetwork.com/article.aspx?articleid=2411288" target="_blank">a report</a> published Tuesday in <em>JAMA</em>.</p>
<p>Medicare, which supports 55 million Americans  --  including 9 million disabled individuals  --  cost the federal government $587.5 billion in 2013. (For more on the program's history, see MedPage Today's <a href="http://www.medpagetoday.com/MedPageTodayat10/Medicareat50/50723" target="_blank">timeline of Medicare reforms</a>.)</p>
<p><strong>FDA Okays Obesity Balloon Device</strong></p>
<p>The <a href="http://www.medpagetoday.com/Endocrinology/Obesity/52820" target="_blank">FDA has approved a gastric balloon</a> to treat obesity, adding to a fat-busting device arsenal that includes gastric banding and a vagal nerve stimulator.</p>
<p>The <a href="http://www.fda.gov/NewsEvents/Newsroom/PressAnnouncements/ucm456296.htm" target="_blank">ReShape dual balloon system</a> is indicated for obese adults who have a body mass index (BMI) of 30 to 40, and at least one other obesity-related comorbidity such as hypertension, high cholesterol, or diabetes.</p>
<div class="ad-slot ad-right tablet-ad"></div><div class="ad-slot ad-right desktop-ad"></div><div class="ad-slot ad-right mobile-ad"></div><p>It's placed into the stomach using an endoscope, and once it's inflated it is meant to diminish obesity by triggering feelings of fullness, "or by other mechanisms that are not yet understood," according to the FDA press release.</p>
<p><strong>Dire Straits: House Panel Mulls Rural Hospitals' Plight</strong></p>
<p>House Democrats and Republicans both agree that <a href="http://www.medpagetoday.com/PublicHealthPolicy/Medicare/52836" target="_blank">rural hospitals are struggling</a> to survive, but their lack of agreement on what's causing the problem was evident at a hearing on Tuesday.</p>
<p>"Our constituents are seeing first-hand the difficulties caused by over-regulation and bureaucracy," <a href="http://www.kevinbrady.house.gov" target="_blank">Rep. Kevin Brady (R-Texas)</a>, chair of the Ways and Means Health Subcommittee, said at the beginning of the subcommittee's hearing on rural health disparities. "And it is our rural neighbors who pay the price when it comes to access."</p>
<p>Brady singled out the so-called "96-hour rule," which requires physicians at critical access hospitals to certify that a particular patient is likely to be discharged or transferred to another hospital within 96 hours of being admitted to the critical access hospital. "That arbitrary cutoff doesn't always match the medical reality for patients seeking treatment at facilities near their homes," he said.</p>
<div class="ad-slot ad-right tablet-ad"></div><div class="ad-slot ad-right desktop-ad"></div><div class="ad-slot ad-right mobile-ad"></div><p><strong>Next Week</strong></p>
<p>Congress will head out on its annual August recess mid-week.</p>
<p>On Thursday and Friday, the <a href="http://www.cbinet.com/conference/pc15063#.VbvIg84rfdk" target="_blank">Benefit Risk Assessment and Decision-Making Summit</a> will meet in Alexandria, Va.</p>
<p>On Friday, the <a href="http://www.allhealth.org/event_reg.asp?bi=369" target="_blank">Alliance for Health Reform</a> will host a briefing on the relationship between health and housing.</p>
